04548nam a22007455i 9780812204995DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)980165318  a97808122049957 a10.9783/97808122049952doi  a(DE-B1597)463536  a(OCoLC)979904819  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a701/.082221 aColbert, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHaunted Visions :bSpiritualism and American Art /cCharles Colbert. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b70 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Arts and Intellectual Life in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: The History and Teachings of Spiritualism -- tChapter 1. Who Speaks for the Dead? -- tChapter 2. Reenchanting America -- tChapter 3. Revelations by Daylight -- tChapter 4. Ghostly Gloamings -- tChapter 5. Land of Promise -- tChapter 6. Romantic Conjurations -- tChapter 7. The Critic as Psychic -- tChapter 8. Lessons in Clairvoyance -- tPostscript -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpiritualism emerged in western New York in 1848 and soon achieved a wide following due to its claim that the living could commune with the dead. In Haunted Visions: Spiritualism and American Art, Charles Colbert focuses on the ways Spiritualism imbued the making and viewing of art with religious meaning and, in doing so, draws fascinating connections between art and faith in the Victorian age.Examining the work of such well-known American artists as James Abbott McNeill Whistler, William Sydney Mount, and Robert Henri, Colbert demonstrates that Spiritualism played a critical role in the evolution of modern attitudes toward creativity. He argues that Spiritualism made a singular contribution to the sanctification of art that occurred in the latter half of the nineteenth century. The faith maintained that spiritual energies could reside in objects, and thus works of art could be appreciated not only for what they illustrated but also as vessels of the psychic vibrations their creators impressed into them. Such beliefs sanctified both the making and collecting of art in an era when Darwinism and Positivism were increasingly disenchanting the world and the efforts to represent it. In this context, Spiritualism endowed the artist's profession with the prestige of a religious calling; in doing so, it sought not to replace religion with art, but to make art a site where religion happened.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt, Americany19th century. 0aSpiritualism in art. 0aSpiritualismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aArchitecture.  aFine Art.  aGarden History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220499540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812204995.jpg  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK